HPA and VPA in K8S?

HPA adds more pods when CPU/memory is high — scales out horizontally with zero downtime, needs Metrics Server to read pod metrics.
VPA resizes CPU/memory of existing pods by killing and recreating them — causes brief downtime unless multiple replicas plus PodDisruptionBudget are used to restart one by one.

Timeline with 4 pods + PDB:

Time 0:  Pod1✅ Pod2✅ Pod3✅ Pod4✅  (all serving)
        ↓
Time 1:  Pod1❌ Pod2✅ Pod3✅ Pod4✅  (Pod1 restarting)
        ↓
Time 2:  Pod1✅ Pod2✅ Pod3✅ Pod4✅  (Pod1 back up)
        ↓
Time 3:  Pod1✅ Pod2❌ Pod3✅ Pod4✅  (Pod2 restarting)
        ↓
Time 4:  Pod1✅ Pod2✅ Pod3✅ Pod4✅  (Pod2 back up)
        ↓
...continues until all 4 updated
        ↓
Zero downtime ✅

--
Without PDB:
  VPA might kill ALL 4 pods at once ❌
  Complete outage ❌

With PDB:
  VPA respects minAvailable
  Restarts one by one ✅
---
If you have 4 pods VPA restarts one by one — combined with PodDisruptionBudget you can achieve near zero downtime!

Full setup for zero downtime VPA:

# 1. Deployment with 4 replicas
apiVersion: apps/v1
kind: Deployment
metadata:
  name: my-app
spec:
  replicas: 4            # ← 4 pods
  template:
    spec:
      containers:
        - name: my-app
          resources:
            requests:
              cpu: "250m"
              memory: "256Mi"
---
# 2. VPA
apiVersion: autoscaling.k8s.io/v1
kind: VerticalPodAutoscaler
metadata:
  name: my-vpa
spec:
  targetRef:
    apiVersion: apps/v1
    kind: Deployment
    name: my-app
  updatePolicy:
    updateMode: "Auto"   # ← restarts pods
---
# 3. PDB — ensures one by one
apiVersion: policy/v1
kind: PodDisruptionBudget
metadata:
  name: my-pdb
spec:
  minAvailable: 3        # ← always 3 running
  selector:
    matchLabels:
      app: my-app

